IRS990.MissionDesc: The Preucil School of Music provides excellence in music and early childhood education based on the Suzuki Philosophy of instruction.
IRS990.Desc: The Preucil School of Music provides music instruction, lessons, programs, workshops and recital opportunities for nearly 630 students ranging from newborns to adults. The school's objectives is to provide music to students at a young age, encourage them to learn music much like their native language, and provide the ability of all individuals to improve their musical talents. The Preucil School of Music is dedicated to the development of ability in all children. The School teaches according to the philosophy of Shinichi Suzuki, who has proven that particular talents are not inborn, and that all children can develop their abilities in music and other areas to a high level if they learn in the manner that they learned to speak their "mother tongue." The Preucil School offers excellence in early childhood education and music instruction for students of all ages in a caring, nurturing environment. It helps parents and children to share in the learning process, serves as a center for involvement in varied early childhood and musical activities, and attempts to create a rich musical and educational environment in the community. Preucil Preschool is a play-based fine arts preschool, inspired by the Reggio approach and the Suzuki Method. The Preschool focuses on creativity, imagination and exploration. The goal is to help each child grow and learn in all areas of human experience as it fosters cooperation, caring, confidence, action, intellect, knowledge, beauty, and inherent motivation. Preucil School offers Music Together(R), an innovative early childhood education program known nationwide and around the world. Using the playful and carefully thought-out series of Music Together classes, specially trained teachers guide young children and the grownups who love them as they experience rhythm, song, culture and community. Each class brings together a small group of parents or caregivers and their children newborn to age 5, guided by a teacher who provides the music, tools and guidance. The "Community Engagement Program" takes the Music Together(R) (MT) program to local parks during the summertime to provide music to underserved children in the community. This program was put on hold in 2020 due to COVID-19, and remains on hold to date. Traditionally, families are able to participate in the park programs for free. This is made possible by the generosity of our donors. The MT program is also provided for free, three times a year, to families enrolled at the local Headstart. Preucil School also provides a music program to the Horace Mann Elementary School's Preschool program during the academic year. The School hopes to eventually bring these community engagement activities back to the parks, Headstart, and Horace Mann Preschool. The Preucil School believes music training is life training, of equal importance to all children regardless of economic status. It aims to keep tuition affordable, and offers aid to those students in need of assistance who demonstrate a desire to learn.

SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: The school has five separate endowment accounts. The main endowment account is established as a permanently restricted fund to earn interest, dividends and capital gains. The board has elected that up to 4.5% of the 60-month rolling average can be used for operations. The second endowment account is a trip fund, established as part temporary and part permanent endowment. The other endowments are financial aid funds, established as part temporary and part permanent endowments.

SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: Each responsible person is required to review the conflict of interest policy and acknowledge in writing that he or she has done so. Each person shall annually complete a disclosure form identifying any relationships that may contribute to a conflict of interest. The policy is to be reviewed by the board annually and any changes in the policy will be communicated to all responsible persons.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Section B, Line 15
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: All positions are reviewed every three to five years to ensure the positions (job descriptions and compensation) are commensurate with the regional and area arts industry. In March of 2019, an extensive survey/review for the instrumental teaching positions at the school was conducted. Survey information came from: The National Guild for Community Arts Education, members of the Suzuki Association of the Americas, Community Music Program of the University of Iowa, West Music Company, Schools and private studio/programs in Iowa City, surrounding area, greater state of Iowa and surrounding states. This survey was presented to the board/finance committee during the budget process. Administrative positions are reviewed on an ongoing basis to ensure the job description meets the job and the pay is commensurate with the experience in the industry. Information comes from programs within the National Guild for Community Schools Arts Education and The Suzuki Association of the Americas. In addition, the University of Iowa and Iowa Workforce Development is used as a reference. Early childhood positions are reviewed on an ongoing basis to ensure the pay is commensurate with the job description. Salary increases are based on the Consumer Price Index. When entry level compensation is established, annual increases are based on the cost of living, performance and additional education (University degrees). Informal reviews are conducted by supervisors who report to the director. Annual compensation for salaried and hourly positions are presented to the finance committee by the director at the time the budget is reviewed for the next year fiscal. After review, the Finance Committee sends the budget onto the Board for their approval.
